[1]
Date: Tue, 15 Dec 1998 14:30:31 +1000
From: SCOTT KITCHENER <KITCHENS@health.qld.gov.au>

While Australians have in the past cared for flying foxes caught in
fences or the like, and this commonly involves caring for infant bats
in the Spring, I have never heard of anyone breast feeding bats, nor
can I imagine such a contribution provides any further assistance in
the matter other than to illustrate Australians as eccentric
egalitarian mammals. The case at hand was [the most recent patient
died on Sunday - Mod.CHC] of a mother certainly, though she
contracted the virus probably when protecting her child from the
attack of a flying fox. When infected with the virus, the bats tend
to be rather erratic in behaviour and more aggressive. This has
previously been (and possibly presently) misdiagnosed as lead
poisoning which is not uncommon in bats living near urban
environments as the particulate pollution carrying lead coats their
fur/hair.
My understanding is that the earliest isolated virus is held by the
Anton Breinl Centre of James Cook University, identified in a frozen
bat initially diagnosed as lead poisoning with encephalopathy.
Returning to the case at hand, a further salient feature is that the
patient was offered post-exposure vaccination shortly after the
exposure and refused to accept [it]. This has fueled a media frenzy
about wider use of pre- and post-exposure vaccination which
presumably will filter out to foreign countries to generate more
alarmist and marginally relevant reports based on minimal fact.
--
Scott Kitchener
Public Health Physician
Queensland
e-mail: <KITCHENS@health.qld.gov.au>
[No doubt there is a media frenzy. Today alone I have spoken with
newspaper and magazine reporters, radio and TV newspeople, and two
kooks, all from Australia. I asked them why they are asking me all
these questions, the Australian scientific community is as competent
as any group to provide accurate and up-to-date information about
Ballina virus. Seems to me that if the scientific community there
would make themselves available for honest, detailed, and
depoliticized information, I wouldn't have to be on the telephone all
day.
The premature death of a human is always a sad affair. However,
taken in context of the larger picture, we are only talking about two
deaths, fewer than occur each day in Australia from physical abuse,
accidental poisoning, and politics. What the Australian scientific
community needs is more funds to do the research at which they are
experts. They seem to be doing an excellent job thus far, given
other priorities they must have.
If there are facts that ProMED-mail has not posted, by all means send
them to us and we will post them at once. For example, we did not
know until today that tissues from archived bats in Melbourne are
being tested by PCR for Ballina virus. We did not know that there
are humans with antibody to Ballina virus but no history of severe
and compatible illness. Instead, we receive messages (the day before
she died) saying "The patient is doing nicely, thank you, so why are
you stirring this pot? - Mod CHC]
