[2]
Date: Tue, 15 Dec 1998 14:03:18 +1000
From: Paul Prociv <p.prociv@mailbox.uq.oz.au>

Just a trivial, but perhaps important, correction. You wrote:
"Bats are common in Australia, particularly the large fruit bats
which inhabit two thirds of the country. As their natural habitat is
being destroyed by man, the bats are moving closer to urban areas.
Colonies have been found in botanic gardens outside Melbourne and
Sydney."

Megabats (pteropids) have always been an integral component of
suburbia here. In fact, cities have been built in what were (and
continue to be) the fruit-bats' foraging territories, and they simply
refuse to be pushed out. In Brisbane (and in Sydney), fruit-bats
swooping around fig, palm and other ornamental, food-bearing trees in
central city streets and parks are a normal feature of the city
nightlife. The Melbourne and Sydney botanical gardens are in the
centres of those cities, not in the outer suburbs! It would be
almost impossible (and perhaps ecologically crazy) to eradicate
these important and beautiful animals, although rednecks and farmers
are always on the lookout for any excuse to attack them
(flame-throwers and dynamite have been used against some roosts
here).

--
Paul Prociv
Assoc Prof, Dept Parasitology
The University of Qld, QLD 4072, AUSTRALIA
Tel: +61 7 3365 3306
Fax: +61 7 3365 1588
<p.prociv@mailbox.uq.oz.au>
