[3]
Date: Mon, 14 Dec 1998 08:34:07 +1000
From: David Dawson <dawsond@health.qld.gov.au>

In summarising the current state of knowledge in the most recent case
of Bat Lyssavirus [i.e., Ballina virus - Mod.CHC] in Queensland, Dr
Calisher stated that "Australians love their flying foxes". My view
would be that it might have been more accurate to say that some
Australians love their flying foxes.
While not having any objective data from a Gallup poll, my guess
would be that a majority of the populace, in particular those in
urban areas, think Australia would be a better place without flying
foxes. It certainly would be quieter and cleaner and those of us who
grow fruit in our backyards would be better nourished!
Flying foxes gather in enormous numbers, hanging almost motionless
from trees during day with their wings folded. They migrate from
these 'camps' at twilight, flying in loose formation, and typically
following river courses. They then disperse, raiding local orchards
and fruit-bearing trees of virtually any description. In populated
areas their incessant screeching can be heard during times normally
set aside for sleeping (humans, that is). Further, flying foxes seem
to have few social graces, to the extent that their semi-liquid
droppings are an eyesore on the sides of homes -- even burning paint
from coated surfaces.
In summary, many of us think flying foxes contribute little to
Australia's wonderful lifestyle.
(This rather light-hearted communication is not intended to deflect
from our concern for the patient who is now seriously ill with
lyssavirus infection.)
--
David Dawson
Brisbane
e-mail: <dawsond@health.qld.gov.au>
[Unfortunately, the patient died. This message might have been meant
to be lighthearted but I didn't take it that way. Australia is no
different from other countries where humans live. Natural landscapes
are changed, flora destroyed, fauna isolated into "reserves", native
people treated as barriers to progress. I am struck by the irony of
Captain Cook and his men considering the place inhospitable.
Although they did not recognize it, the places they so described were
not inhospitable to native humans, trees, bushes, grasses, goannas,
insects, birds, or macropods; it was inhospitable to them. Therefore,
in the great tradition of the human species, and in an effort to make
the place more hospitable to themselves, Australians have altered the
environment so that it is less inhospitable to Caucasians and some
others. However, it is now more inhospitable to native humans,
trees, bushes, grasses, goannas, insects, birds, and macropods.
The sentiments expressed in this message should give one reason to
pause and ask what the hell we are doing? One more thing: If they
could be asked, I'd like to know what flying foxes think about our
contribution to their wonderful lifestyle.
Unless we receive data regarding the emergence of Ballina virus, this
string is cut - Mod.CHC]
